{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.13,0.08,0.04,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57890"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"3188"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic following an episode earlier that day where she suddenly lost consciousness for approximately 10 seconds. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her parent reports that during the episode, she appeared vacant and inaccessible with fluttering of her eyelids. At the end of the episode, she immediately returned to normal consciousness with no confusion. She has no recollection of the event.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of seizure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal lobe seizure","Tonic clonic seizure","Myoclonic seizure","Extratemporal seizure","Absence seizure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is typical of an absence seizure, characterised by a brief loss of consciousness with sudden onset and offset, accompanied by eyelid fluttering. These seizures typically last 5-20 seconds and are followed by immediate return to normal consciousness without post-ictal confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence seizures\u003C/strong\u003E are most common in children and adolescents. They are generalised seizures that involve both cerebral hemispheres simultaneously. The characteristic electroencephalogram (EEG) finding is a 3 Hz spike-and-wave pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal lobe seizures\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with an aura followed by altered consciousness, automatisms (such as lip smacking or picking at clothes), and post-ictal confusion. They usually last longer than absence seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonic clonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E involve loss of consciousness with rigid extension of limbs (tonic phase) followed by rhythmic jerking (clonic phase). They are typically longer in duration and associated with post-ictal confusion, muscle soreness, and fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyoclonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E are characterised by sudden, brief muscle jerks or twitches, without loss of consciousness. They often occur in clusters and may affect one part of the body or the whole body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtratemporal seizures\u003C/strong\u003E originate outside the temporal lobe and can have various manifestations depending on the location of onset. They typically have focal symptoms related to the area of the brain involved and may spread to become generalised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Absence seizures are characterised by brief episodes of sudden loss of consciousness with rapid recovery.","Eyelid fluttering is a common feature of absence seizures.","Absence seizures typically last less than 20 seconds and occur without warning or post-ictal confusion."],"references":["Kammerman S, Wasserman L. Seizure disorders: Part 1. Classification and diagnosis. West J Med. 2001 Aug;175(2):99-103. doi: 10.1136/ewjm.175.2.99. PMID: 11483551; PMCID: PMC1071497.","Fisher RS, Cross JH, French JA, Higurashi N, Hirsch E, Jansen FE, Lagae L, Mosh\u00e9 SL, Peltola J, Roulet Perez E, Scheffer IE, Zuberi SM. Operational classification of seizure types by the International League Against Epilepsy: Position Paper of the ILAE Commission for Classification and Terminology. Epilepsia. 2017 Apr;58(4):522-530. doi: 10.1111/epi.13670. Epub 2017 Mar 8. PMID: 28276060.","Sarmast ST, Abdullahi AM, Jahan N. Current Classification of Seizures and Epilepsies: Scope, Limitations and Recommendations for Future Action. Cureus. 2020 Sep 20;12(9):e10549. doi: 10.7759/cureus.10549. PMID: 33101797; PMCID: PMC7575300.","Huff JS, Murr NI. Seizure. 2023 Feb 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613516.","Tenney JR, Glauser TA. The current state of absence epilepsy: can we have your attention? Epilepsy Curr. 2013 May;13(3):135-40. doi: 10.5698/1535-7511-13.3.135. PMID: 23840175; PMCID: PMC3697883."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57890"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"t